ign=\"right\"|6,212\n|-\n|28 (7)\n|[[Korangi District|Korangi]]\n|[[Korangi Town]]\n|align=\"right\"|95\n|align=\"right\"|2,457,019\n|align=\"right\"|25,918\n|-\n|29 (7)\n|[[Malir District|Malir]]\n|[[Malir Town]]\n|align=\"right\"|2,635\n|align=\"right\"|2,008,901\n|align=\"right\"|762\n|}\n\n== Economy ==\n{{main|Economy of Sindh}}\n[[File: Karachi downtown.jpeg|thumb|A view of Karachi downtown, the capital of Sindh province]]\n[[File:GDP by Province.jpg|300px|thumb|left|GDP by province]]\n[[File:Qayoom_Abad_Bridge.JPG|thumb|Qayoom Abad Bridge Karachi]]\n[[File:Navalrai_Market_Clock_Tower_view_1.JPG|thumb|Navalrai Market Clock Tower Hyderabad]]\nSindh has the [[List of Pakistani provinces by GDP|second largest economy]] in Pakistan. A 2016 study commissioned by Pakistan Ministry of Planning found that urban Sindh and northern Punjab province are the most prosperous regions in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Northern Punjab, urban Sindh people more prosperous than rest of country: report|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1126363/people-living-northern-punjab-urban-sindh-prosperous-rest-country-report/|accessdate=15 December 2017|agency=Express Tribune|date=20 June 2016}}</ref> Its GDP per capita was $1,400 in 2010 which is 50 percent more than the rest of the nation or 35 percent more than the national average. Historically, Sindh's contribution to Pakistan's GDP has been between 30% to 32.7%. Its share in the service sector has ranged from 21% to 27.8% and in the agriculture sector from 21.4% to 27.7%. Performance wise, its best sector is the manufacturing sector, where its share has ranged from 36.7% to 46.5%.\n\nEndowed with coastal access, Sindh is a major centre of economic activity in Pakistan and has a highly diversified economy ranging from heavy industry and finance centred in Karachi to a substantial agricultural base along the [[Indus River|Indus]]. Manufacturing includes machine products, cement, plastics, and other goods.\n\nAgriculture is very important in Sindh with [[cotton]], [[rice]], [[wheat]], [[sugar cane]], [[date (fruit)|dates]], [[banana]]s, and [[mango]]es as the most important crops. The largest and finer quality of rice is produced in [[Larkana|Larkano]] district.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eU3RAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA226|title=Gazetteer of the Province of Sind \u2026|date=1907|publisher=government at the \"Mercantile\" steam Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Sindh|url=http://karachi.chineseconsulate.org/eng/lqgk/t264253.htm|website=Consulate General of the People's Republic of China in Karachi|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n[[Image:429068485 5f192dcf9f o.jpg|thumb|Dayaram Jethmal College (D.J. College), Karachi in the 19th century]]\n[[Image:Hindu Gymkhana Karachi.jpeg|thumb|[[National Academy of Performing Arts]], Karachi]]\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year||Literacy rate\n|-\n|1972||60.77\n|-\n|1981||37.5%\n|-\n|1998||45.29%\n|-\n|2008||60.7%\n|-\n|2012||69.50%\n|}\n\nThe following is a chart of the education market of Sindh estimated by the government in 1998:<ref name=\"statpak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/pco/statistics/pop_education/pop_education_rural_urban.html |title=Population by Level of Education and Rural/Urban |publisher=Statistics Division: Ministry of Economic Affairs and Statistics. Government of Pakistan |accessdate=2009-08-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090720044627/http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/pco/statistics/pop_education/pop_education_rural_urban.html |archivedate=July 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Qualification||Urban||Rural||Total||Enrollment ratio (%)\n|-\n|\u2014||'''14,839,862'''||'''15,600,031'''||'''30,439,893'''||\u2014\n|-\n|Below Primary||1,984,089||3,332,166||5,316,255||100.00\n|-\n|Primary||3,503,691||5,687,771||9,191,462||82.53\n|-\n|Middle||3,073,335||2,369,644||5,442,979||52.33\n|-\n|Matriculation||2,847,769||2,227,684||5,075,453||34.45\n|-\n|Intermediate||1,473,598||1,018,682||2,492,280||17.78\n|-\n|Diploma, Certificate...||1,320,747||552,241||1,872,988||9.59\n|-\n|BA, BSc... degrees||440,743||280,800||721,543||9.07\n|-\n|MA, MSc... degrees||106,847||53,040||159,887||2.91\n|-\n|Other qualifications||89,043||78,003||167,046||0.54\n|}\n\nMajor public and private educational institutes in Sindh include:\n\n{{Colbegin|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Adamjee Government Science College]]\n* [[Aga Khan University]]\n* [[APIIT]]\n* [[Applied Economics Research Centre]]\n* [[Bahria University]]\n* [[Baqai Medical University]]\n* [[Chandka Medical College|Chandka Medical College Larkana]]\n* [[Cadet College Petaro]]\n* College of Digital Sciences\n* [[College of Physicians & Surgeons Pakistan]]\n* [[COMMECS Institute of Business and Emerging Sciences]]\n* [[D. J. Science College]]\n* [[Dawood College of Engineering and Technology]]\n* [[Defence Authority Degree College for Men]]\n* [[Dow International Medical College]]\n* [[Dow University of Health Sciences]]\n* [[Fatima Jinnah Dental College]]\n* [[Federal Urdu University]]\n* GBELS Dourai Mahar Taluka Daur Distt: Shaheed Benazirabad\n* [[Ghulam Muhammad Mahar Medical College Sukkur]]\n* [[Government College for Men Nazimabad]]\n* Government College Hyderabad\n* [[Government College of Commerce & Economics]]\n* [[Government College of Technology, Karachi]]\n* Government Degree College Matiari\n* [[Government High School Ranipur]]\n* [[Government Islamia Science College Sukkur]]\n* Government Muslim Science College Hyderabad\n* [[Government National College (Karachi)]]\n* Greenwich University (Karachi)\n* [[Hamdard University]]\n* [[Hussain Ebrahim Jamal Research Institute of Chemistry]]\n* Imperial Science College Nawabshah\n* [[Indus Valley Institute of Art and Architecture]]\n* [[Institute of Business Administration, Karachi]]\n* [[Institute of Business Administration, Sukkar]]\n* [[Institute of Business Management]]\n* [[Institute of Industrial Electronics Engineering]]\n* [[Institute of Sindhology]]\n* [[Iqra University]]\n* [[Islamia Science College (Karachi)]]\n* [[Isra University Hyderabad]]\n* [[Jinnah Medical & Dental College]]\n* [[Jinnah Polytechnic Institute]]\n* [[Jinnah Post Graduate Medical Centre]]\n* [[Jinnah University for Women]]\n* [[KANUPP Institute of Nuclear Power Engineering]]\n* [[Karachi School of Business and Leadership]]\n* [[Liaquat University of Medical & Health Sciences]]\n* [[Mehran University of Engineering and Technology]]\n* [[Mohammad Ali Jinnah University]]\n* [[National Academy of Performing Arts]]\n* [[National University of Computer and Emerging Sciences]]\n* [[National University of Modern Languages]]\n* [[National University of Sciences and Technology, Pakistan|National University of Sciences and Technology]]\n* [[NED University of Engineering and Technology]]\n* Ojha Institute of Chest Diseases\n* PAF Institute of Aviation Technology\n* TES Public School, Daur\n* PAF KIET- Karachi Institute of Economics and Technology\n* [[Pakistan Navy Engineering College]]\n* [[Pakistan Shipowners' College]]\n* [[Pakistan Steel Cadet College]]\n* Peoples Medical College for Girls Nawabshah\n* PIA Training Centre Karachi\n* Provincial Institute of Teachers Education Nawabshah\n* Public School Hyderabad\n* [[Quaid-e-Awam University of Engineering, Science and Technology]], [[Nawabshah]]\n* [[Rana Liaquat Ali Khan Government College of Home Economics]]\n* [[Saint Patrick's College, Karachi]]\n* [[Shah Abdul Latif Bhitai University]]\n* [[Shaheed Benazir Bhutto Medical College]]\n* [[Shaheed Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto Institute of Science and Technology]]\n* [[Sindh Agriculture University]]\n* [[Sindh Medical College]]\n* Superior College of Science Hyderabad\n* [[Sindh Muslim Law College]]\n* [[Sir Syed Government Girls College]]\n* [[Sir Syed University of Engineering and Technology]]\n* [[St. Joseph's College (Karachi)|St. Joseph's College]]\n* [[Sukkur Institute of Science & Technology]]\n* [[Textile Institute of Pakistan]]\n* [[University of Karachi]]\n* [[University of Sindh]]\n* [[Usman Institute of Technology]]\n* [[Ziauddin Medical University]]\n{{Colend}}\n\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Children in a village, Sindh, Pakistan, April 2012 (8405077775).jpg|thumb|right|Children in a rural area of Sindh, 2012]]\nThe rich culture, art and architectural landscape of Sindh have fascinated historians. The culture, folktales, art and music of Sindh form a mosaic of human history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/610452/spotlighting-sindh-exhibit-provides-peek-into-provinces-rich-culture/|title=Spotlighting: Sindh Exhibit provides peek into province's rich culture \u2013 The Express Tribune|date=2013-09-28|work=The Express Tribune|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Cultural heritage ===\n{{Main|Sindhi culture}}\n[[File:Archaeological Ruins at Moenjodaro-108221.jpg|thumb|Archaeological ruins at Moenjodaro, Sindh, [[Pakistan]]]]\n[[File:Bhambore1.JPG|thumb|The ruins of an ancient mosque at [[Bhambore]]]]\n[[File:Women in Sindh.jpg|thumb|Sindhi women collecting water from a reservoir on the way to Mubarak Village]]\n\nSindh has a rich heritage of traditional handicraft that has evolved over the centuries. Perhaps the most professed exposition of Sindhi culture is in the handicrafts of [[Haala|Hala]], a town some 30 kilometres from [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]]. Hala's artisans manufacture high-quality and impressively priced wooden handicrafts, textiles, paintings, handmade paper products, and blue pottery. Lacquered wood works known as Jandi, painting on wood, tiles, and pottery known as Kashi, hand weaved textiles including ''[[khadi]]'', ''susi'', and ''[[ajrak]]s'' are synonymous with Sindhi culture preserved in Hala's handicraft.\n\nThe work of Sindhi artisans was sold in ancient markets of Damascus, Baghdad, Basra, Istanbul, Cairo and Samarkand. Referring to the lacquer work on wood locally known as Jandi, T. Posten (an English traveller who visited Sindh in the early 19th century) asserted that the articles of Hala could be compared with exquisite specimens of China. Technological improvements such as the spinning wheel ([[Charkha (spinning wheel)|charkha]]) and treadle (pai-chah) in the weaver's loom were gradually introduced and the processes of designing, dyeing and printing by block were refined. The refined, lightweight, colourful, washable fabrics from Hala became a luxury for people used to the woollens and linens of the age.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wishwebdesign.com/dgaewm/otherinfo/Cultural-Heritage/542/533|title=Cultural Heritage|author= |date=|website=wishwebdesign.com = |accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nNon-governmental organisations (NGOs) such as the World Wildlife Fund, Pakistan,  play an important role to promote the culture of Sindh. They provide training to women artisans in the interior of Sindh so they get a source of income. They promote their products under the name of \"Crafts Forever\". Many women in rural Sindh are skilled in the production of caps. Sindhi caps are manufactured commercially on a small scale at New Saeedabad and Hala New. These are in demand with visitors from Karachi and other places; however, these manufacturing units have a limited production capacity. Sindhi people began celebrating Sindhi Topi Day on December 6, 2009, to preserve the historical culture of Sindh by wearing Ajrak and Sindhi topi.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/pakistan/provinces/13+sindh+celebrates+first+ever+sindhi+topi+day-za-04|title= Sindh celebrates first ever 'Sindhi Topi Day'}}</ref>\n\n[[File:House in the Thar.JPG|thumb|Huts in the Thar desert]]\n\n== Places of interest ==\n{{See also|Places of historical interest in Sindh}}\n\nTourist sites include the ruins of [[Mohenjo-daro]] near the city of [[Larkana]], Runi Kot, Kot Deji, the Jain temples of Nangar Parker and the historic temple of Sadhu Bela, Sukkur. Islamic architecture is quite prominent in the province; its numerous mausoleums include the ancient [[Shahbaz Qalander]] mausoleum.\n* [[Sachal Sarmast]] ( Sufi poet ) Daraz near Ranipur\n{{Colbegin|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Aror]] (ruins of historical city) near [[Sukkur]]\n* Chaukandi Tombs, Karachi\n* Do darya, [[Karachi]]\n* Forts at [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]] and [[Umarkot]]\n* [[Gorakh Hill]] in [[Dadu District|Dadu]]\n* [[Kahu-Jo-Darro]] near [[Mirpurkhas]]\n* [[Kirthar National Park]] in [[Dadu District|Dadu]]\n* [[Kot Diji Fort]], [[Kot Diji]]\n* [[Kotri Barrage]] near Hyderabad\n* [[Makli Hill]], Asia's largest [[necropolis]], [[Makli Hill|Makli, Thatta]]\n* [[Mazar-e-Quaid]], Karachi\n* Minar-e-Mir Masum Shah, Sukkur\n* [[Mohatta Palace Museum]], Karachi\n* [[Rani Bagh, Hyderabad|Rani Bagh]], Hyderabad\n* [[Ranikot Fort]] near Sann\n* Ruins of [[Mohenjo-daro]] and Museum near Larkana\n* [[Pakka Qila]], Hyderabad\n* Sadhu Bela Temple near Sukkur\n* [[Shahjahan Mosque]], [[Thatta]]\n* Shrine of [[Allama Makhdoom Muhammad Hashim Thattvi]], [[Thatta]]\n* Shrine of [[Shah Inayat Shaheed]],  [[Jhok]]\n* Shrine of [[Shah Abdul Latif Bhitai]], [[Bhit|Bhit Shah]]\n* Shrine of [[Shahbaz Qalander]] in [[Sehwan]], [[Dadu District|Dadu]]\n* [[Sukkur Barrage]], Sukkur\n* Talpurs' Faiz Mahal Palace, [[Khayrpur (princely state)|Khairpur]]\n{{Colend}}\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:FaizMahal.jpg|Faiz Mahal, [[Khairpur, Pakistan|Khairpur]]\nFile:Ranikot Fort 07a.jpg|[[Ranikot Fort]], one of the largest forts in the world\nFile:Chaukundi1.JPG|[[Chaukhandi tombs]]\nFile:Bhodesar temple, Nagarparkar.JPG|Remains of [[9th century]] [[Jainism|Jain]] [[Nagarparkar Jain Temples|temple]] in Bhodesar near [[Nagarparkar]].\nFile:Keenjhar Lake Thatta.jpg|[[Keenjhar Lake]], Thatta\nFile:Mohenjodaro Sindh.jpeg|Excavated ruins of [[Mohenjo-daro]]\nFile:Kanab beach.JPG|Karachi Beach\nFile:QASIM Fort.JPG|[[Qasim fort]]\nFile:Fort-detail.jpg|[[Kot Diji]]\nFile:Sukkur on the Indus.jpeg|West bank of the [[River Indus]]\nFile:Bakirwarolake.jpg|Bakri Waro Lake, Khairpur\nFile:Khi National Museum.jpg|[[National Museum of Pakistan]]\nFile:Kirthar National Park.jpg|[[Kirthar National Park]]\nFile:Karoonjhar Mountains.jpg|alt=Karoonjhar Mountains, Tharparkar|[[Karoonjhar Mountains]], [[Tharparkar]]\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Bagh Print]]s\n* [[Brahma from Mirpur-Khas]]\n* [[Debal]]\n* [[Government of Sindh]]\n* [[Gurjara-Pratihara]]\n* [[Indus River]]\n* [[Institute of Sindhology]]\n* [[List of cities in Sindh]]\n* [[List of districts of Pakistan]]\n* [[List of Sindhi people]]\n* [[Mansura, Sindh]]\n* [[Mohenjodaro]]\n* [[Mughal Empire]]\n* [[Muhajir Sooba]]\n* [[Sind Province (1936\u201355)]]\n* [[Sind Division]]\n* [[Sindhu Kingdom]]\n* [[Sufism in Sindh]]\n* [[Sindh (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Sindhi dress]]\n* [[Tomb paintings of Sindh]]\n* [[Western Satraps]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Geography|Asia|Pakistan}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n* Ansari, Sarah F.D. (1992) ''Sufi saints and state power: the pirs of Sind, 1843\u20131947'', No. 50. Cambridge University Press: Cambridge. {{ISBN|9780511563201}}.\n* {{citation |author=Phiroze Vasunia|title=The Classics and Colonial India|date=16 May 2013|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-01-9920-323-9|ref={{sfnref|Phiroze Vasunia|2013}}}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Sindh Story|first=Kewal Ram|last=Malkani|authorlink=K. R. Malkani|publisher=Allied Publishers Pvt. Ltd.|year=1984}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|voy=Sindh}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121119234920/http://www.transport.gos.pk/ Sindh Transport Department official website]\n* [http://www.sindh.gov.pk Government of Sindh]\n* Guide of [http://dmoz.pk/Provinces/Sindh/ Sindh]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091126053250/http://www.lgdsindh.com.pk/districts1.htm Map of the districts of Sindh]\n* {{curlie|Regional/Asia/Pakistan/Provinces/Sindh}}\n* [http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Pakistan_states.html#Sind WorldStatesmen \u2013 Pakistan \u2013 Provinces : Sindh]\n\n{{Sindh topics}}\n{{Administrative units of Pakistan}}\n{{Districts of Sindh}}\n{{Pakistan topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Provinces of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sindh| ]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 7th millennium BC]]\n[[Category:7th-millennium BC establishments]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Philisophy \u2192 Philosophy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindh"}
{"title_page": "Joanne Froggatt", "text_new": "{{Short description|English actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Joanne Froggatt\n| image           = Joanne Froggatt May 3, 2014 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize       = 220px\n| caption         = Froggatt in May 2014\n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|8|23}}\n| birth_place     = [[Littlebeck, North Yorkshire|Littlebeck]], England\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| nationality     = British\n| other_names     = \n| occupation      = Actress\n| yearsactive     = 1996\u2013present\n| spouse          = {{Marriage|James Cannon|2012}}<ref name=\"YP14sep14\"/>\n| domesticpartner = \n| children        = \n| parents         = \n| notable_works   = ''[[Coronation Street]]'' <br> ''[[Dinnerladies (TV series)|Dinnerladies]]'' <br> ''[[Life on Mars (British TV series)|Life on Mars]]'' <br> ''[[See No Evil: The Moors Murders]]'' <br>''[[Downton Abbey]]'' <br> ''[[The Royle Family]]'' <br>''[[Bob the Builder]]'' <br> ''[[Liar (TV series)|Liar]]''\n| website         = {{URL|www.joannefroggatt.com/}}\n}}\n'''Joanne Froggatt''' (born 23 August 1980) is an English actress. From 2010 to 2015, she portrayed Anna Bates in the [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] period drama series ''[[Downton Abbey]]''. For this role, she received three [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy]] nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]], and won the [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress - Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress on Television]] in 2014. From 2017, she has starred in the ITV drama series ''[[Liar (TV series)|Liar]]''.\n\nFroggatt's early television appearances include ''[[Coronation Street]]'' (1997\u20131998), ''[[Bad Girls (TV series)|Bad Girls]]'' (1999), ''[[Dinnerladies (TV series)|Dinnerladies]]'' (1999) and ''[[A Touch of Frost]]'' (2003). She went on to star in the television films ''[[Danielle Cable: Eyewitness]]'' (2003), ''[[See No Evil: The Moors Murders]]'' (2006) and ''[[Murder in the Outback]]'' (2007), before winning the [[British Independent Film Award]] for Most Promising Newcomer for her leading role in the 2010 film ''[[In Our Name]]''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFroggatt was born and brought up in the village of [[Littlebeck, North Yorkshire|Littlebeck]]<ref name=bornl>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Andy|title=Wensleydale Railway, at Leeming Bar used for TV filming|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/northyorkshire/4750472.Crew_shoots_scenes_for_Iraq_return_film_at_rail_station/|accessdate=5 September 2017|newspaper=Northern Echo|date=20 November 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Guard230806\">{{cite news |last=Maynard |first=Roger |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/aug/23/broadcasting.ITV |title=Backpacker murder ordeal to be made into TV drama |publisher=The Guardian |location=UK |date=23 August 2006|access-date=5 September 2017}}</ref> in [[North Yorkshire]]. Her parents, Ann and Keith Froggatt, having run a corner shop, next started a rare breed sheep farm on a smallholding near [[Whitby]].<ref name=\"WG010808\"/> Joanne has likened her childhood setting to the backdrop of [[Emily Bront\u00eb]]'s classic novel ''[[Wuthering Heights]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/tv/joanne-froggatt-downton-abbey-star-getting-married-in-real-life/|title=Joanne Froggatt of Downton Abbey: Five Things to Know About Anna Bates|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=27 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> Froggatt initially joined a drama group in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]]<ref name=pinny>{{cite news |last=Gilert |first=Gerard |title=The housemaid's tale: Joanne Froggatt rips off her pinny and sets her sights on Hollywood |publisher=The Independent |location=UK |date=24 March 2012 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/the-housemaids-tale-joanne-froggatt-rips-off-her-pinny-and-sets-her-sights-on-hollywood-7580542.html}}</ref> and then left her family home at the age of 13 to attend the [[Redroofs Theatre School]] in [[Maidenhead]], Berkshire.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1996, Froggatt made her TV debut in the long-running [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] drama ''[[The Bill]]'', and shortly afterwards landed the role of teenage mother [[Zoe Tattersall (Coronation Street)|Zoe Tattersall]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''. She left the programme in 1998 when her character was written out.<ref name=pinny/> In 1999, she appeared in the first four episodes of the first series of prison drama ''[[Bad Girls (TV series)|Bad Girls]]'', portraying teenage mother [[Rachel Hicks]] who suffered endless bullying and committed suicide.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 2003, Froggatt played the leading role in the controversial one-off drama, ''[[Danielle Cable: Eyewitness]]'', based on the true story of a teenage girl who witnessed the murder of her boyfriend in a reputed [[road rage]] attack. Whilst researching the role, she met Cable who later contacted her to commend her on her portrayal.<ref>{{cite news|title=M25 murder fianc\u00e9e backs drama|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/2869683.stm|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=BBC News|date=20 March 2003}}</ref> The film earned a [[British Academy Television Award|BAFTA TV Award]] nomination for Best Single Drama.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winners announced at British Academy Craft Awards|url=http://www.headline-pictures.co.uk/downloads/BAFTA_Press_Release_040518.pdf|website=headlinepictures.co.uk|publisher=BAFTA|accessdate=5 September 2017|page=5|date=16 April 2004}}</ref>\n\nFroggatt played the role of Angelique Mahy in the ITV mini-series ''[[Island at War]]'', that tells the story of the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]]. It aired on 11 July 2004. In the same year she played Myra in the [[BBC Radio 4]] drama ''[[My Turn to Make the Tea]]'' by [[Monica Dickens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=My Turn to Make the Tea \u2013 BBC Radio 4 FM \u2013 15 September 2004 \u2013 BBC Genome|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/368c768b1ff3499fb53f0a23f223106b|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nFroggatt starred as a main character in the drama ''Missing'', made by [[SMG Productions]] in 2006 alongside [[Gregor Fisher]]. However, the two-part thriller was not broadcast on [[STV (TV network)|STV]] until November 2008 because ITV had changed its format to 60-minute time slots and Missing was two 90-minute time slots.<ref>{{cite web|title=Missing \u2013 S1 \u2013 Episode 1|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/tyvn8/missing--series-1---episode-1/|website=Radio Times|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Drama Production from stv \u2013 allmediascotland\u2026media jobs, media release service and media resources for all|url=http://www.allmediascotland.com/digital-media/15774/new-drama-production-from-stv/|website=www.allmediascotland.com|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2006, Froggatt played the sister of [[Myra Hindley]] in the ITV drama, ''[[See No Evil: The Moors Murders]]'', and later appeared in another controversial role as the title character in ''[[Joanne Lees: Murder in the Outback]]'', which first aired on [[Network Ten|Channel Ten]] in Australia on 18 March 2007, and was screened in Britain on ITV on 8 April 2007.<ref name=\"Guard230806\"/> The role involved the depiction of a real-life kidnap, in which Froggatt had to perform scenes tied up with [[tape gag|tape around her mouth as a gag]] She also appeared on the London stage in the adaptation of ''[[All About My Mother]]'' in the part of Sister Rosa, which ran from July to November 2007 at the [[Old Vic]] Theatre.<ref>{{cite news|title=First Night: All About My Mother, Old Vic, London|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/first-night-all-about-my-mother-old-vic-london-401440.html|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Independent|date=5 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nFroggatt portrayed Kate, a peasant, in the third season of the BBC TV series ''[[Robin Hood (2006 TV series)|Robin Hood]]''.<ref name=\"WG010808\">{{cite news |last=Stokoe |first=Jon |url=http://www.whitbygazette.co.uk/news/Joanne-Froggatt-to-star-in.4345799.jp |title=Joanne Froggatt to star in Robin Hood |publisher=Johnston Publishing Ltd. |website=Whitby Gazette |location=UK |date=1 August 2008 |accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref>\nShe played Hannah, in ''[[Spooks: Code 9]]'', and features in the BBC Radio adaptation of ''Solaris'' as Rheya. In May 2009, she played Kelly on [[BBC]] drama ''[[Moving On (TV series)|Moving On]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC \u2013 Press Office \u2013 Moving On press pack: Joanne Froggatt|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/04_april/15/moving6.shtml|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2009, Froggatt played the title role in the BBC Radio Four play ''I am Emma Humphreys''. On 3 October of that year, Froggatt played Princess Yvonne in the BBC Radio Four Saturday play ''The Von Trapps and Me''.<ref>{{cite web | title=Saturday Play: The Von Trapps and Me | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00mz3pq | publisher=BBC | date= | accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 2010, Froggatt appeared opposite [[Lee Ingleby]] in the BBC Radio Four play ''The Disappearance by Peter Walley''. In her film d\u00e9but, ''[[In Our Name]]'', Froggatt played Suzy, a soldier suffering from [[post-traumatic stress disorder]]. She garnered critical acclaim for her performance and won Best Newcomer at the British Independent Film Awards.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=In Our Name \u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/dec/09/in-our-name-film-review|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Guardian|date=9 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Masters|first1=Tim|title=King's Speech reigns at British Independent Film awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11922410|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=BBC News|date=6 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 2010, Froggatt appeared in ''[[Downton Abbey]]'' as Anna, lady's maid to Lady Mary Crawley, for which she received an [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy]] nomination in both 2012 and 2014. On 11 January 2015 she was awarded the [[Golden Globe]] for Best Supporting Actress in a Series, Mini-Series or TV Movie for the role.<ref name=\":TT:\">{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Sally|title=Joanne Froggatt: 'The end of Downton Abbey is a bit strange \u2013 there is an element of grieving'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/downton-abbey/11864183/Joanne-Froggatt-interview-Downton-Abbey-ending-last-series.html|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=20 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 December 2010, Froggatt appeared in the ''[[Royle Family]]'' Christmas special \"Joe's Crackers\" as Saskia, the girlfriend of Antony Royle. Despite having been mentioned by name in earlier episodes, this was the first time that Saskia had appeared in person.<ref name=\":TI:\">{{cite news|last1=Gilert|first1=Gerard|title=The housemaid's tale: Joanne Froggatt rips off her pinny and sets her|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/the-housemaids-tale-joanne-froggatt-rips-off-her-pinny-and-sets-her-sights-on-hollywood-7580542.html|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Independent|date=24 March 2012}}</ref> Froggatt starred in John Donnelly's play ''The Knowledge'' at the [[Bush Theatre]], West London from 12 January to 19 February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spencer|first1=Charles|title=The Knowledge, Bush Theatre, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/8267623/The-Knowledge-Bush-Theatre-review.html|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=18 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlong with ''Downton Abbey'' in 2013, Froggatt also had roles in the comedy drama based on [[Irvine Welsh]]'s novel, ''[[Filth (film)|Filth]]'', in the thriller ''[[uwantme2killhim?]]'' and the indie directed by [[Uberto Pasolini]], ''[[Still Life (2013 film)|Still Life]]''.<ref name=\":TI:\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Peter|title=Still Life review \u2013 Eddie Marsan in a sad search for the bereaved |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/05/still-life-review-eddie-marsan-joanne-froggatt |accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Guardian|date=5 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she played Wendy in the new ''[[Bob the Builder]]'' series voicing her in both the UK and US versions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Furness|first1=Hannah|title=Bob the Builder gets an equality makeover as Wendy wins promotion|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/23/bob-the-builder-gets-an-equality-makeover-as-wendy-wins-promotio/|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=23 June 2016}}</ref> In 2016 she starred in a two part ITV miniseries ''[[Dark Angel (British TV series)|Dark Angel]]'', based on the true story of Victorian poisoner [[Mary Ann Cotton]]. Also in 2016 she co-starred in a dramatisation of a real-life story \"Starfish\" as Nic, wife of Tom Ray who was struck down with [[sepsis]] and left with life-changing disabilities.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 2017, Froggatt appeared in the lead role of schoolteacher Laura Neilson in the six-part thriller miniseries ''[[Liar (TV series)|Liar]]'' on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]. Her character awakens convinced that she was raped by respected surgeon Dr Andrew Earlham ([[Ioan Gruffudd]]) \u2013 who also happens to be the father of one of her students \u2013 even though she can't remember the incident, nor does forensic evidence bear out her version of events. The series aired in the U.S. on [[SundanceTV]].\n\nFroggatt made her stage debut on 25 February 2019 as Frances Thorpe in the thriller [[Alys, Always]] at the [[Bridge Theatre]] in London. The play was directed by [[Nicholas Hytner]] and written by [[Lucinda Coxon]] and based on the book by [[Harriet Lane (author)|Harriet Lane]].\n\n==Personal life==\nFroggatt married long-time boyfriend James Cannon in a private ceremony in October 2012.<ref name=\"YP14sep14\">{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/what-s-on/theatre/joanne-froggatt-robin-hood-s-bay-to-downton-abbey-1-6832407|title=Joanne Froggatt: Robin Hood's Bay to Downton Abbey|work=The Yorkshire Post|date=14 September 2014|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> In February 2020, she confirmed they had separated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/culture/a30831117/downton-abbey-joanne-froggatt-split-james-cannon/|title=Downton Abbey's Joanne Froggatt confirms split from husband James Cannon|first=Naomi|last=Gordon|date=9 February 2020|website=Harper's BAZAAR}}</ref>\n\n==Charity==\nIn 2013 Froggatt became an ambassador for global children's charity Plan UK's \"Because I Am a Girl\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://plan-international.org/because-i-am-a-girl|title=Downton star to help world's girls|last=|first=|date=19 September 2013|website=|publisher=Plan UK|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n\n===Audio drama===\n\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Solaris'' || Rheya || BBC Radio 4 Extra\n|-\n| 2010 || \"The Disappearance\" || Alice || BBC Radio 4\n|-\n| 2014 || ''The Extraordinary Adventures of G.A. Henty: In Freedom's Cause'' || Lady Marjory || (post-production)\n|-\n| 2014 || ''Shirley'' || Caroline || BBC Radio 4\n\n|}\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Miranda (2002 film)|Miranda]]'' || Jacquie || \n|-\n| 2009 || ''Echoes'' || Anya || Short film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[In Our Name]]'' || Suzy || [[British Independent Film Awards|British Independent Film Award for Most Promising Newcomer]]\n|-\