{"title_page": "Stats Perform", "text_new": "{{short description|US sports technology and data company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Stats Perform\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| logo_padding        = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founded             = {{start date|1981|04|30}}\n| founder             = John Dewan\n| hq_location         = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| hq_location_city    = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = Carl Mergele (CEO)\n| industry            = Sports Technology and Data\n| products            = Sports data, analytics and team tracking solutions\n| brands              = Omnisports, [[Opta Sports]], [[Prozone Sports Ltd|Prozone]], [[TVTI]], [[Automated Insights]], [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]], [[BSports]]\n| services            = \n| owner               = Vista Equity Partners\n| website             = {{URL|statsperform.com}}\n| former_name         = \n}}\n\n'''Stats Perform''' (formerly '''STATS LLC''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=739452|title=STATS LLC: Private Company Information|website=[[Bloomberg.com]]|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref> is a [[Chicago]]-based sports data and [[sports analytics|analytics]] company.\n\nThe company is involved in sports data collection and [[Predictive analytics|predictive analysis]], and maintains sports-oriented [[wire service]]s. The company has also been increasingly involved in [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]].<ref name=\"sporttechie.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sporttechie.com/the-evolution-of-stats-llc-and-its-place-in-the-sports-technology-landscape/|title=The Evolution of STATS LLC And Its Place In The Sports Technology Landscape|website=SportTechie|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Its clients include media outlets, sports leagues and teams, [[fantasy sports]] and [[sports betting]] services. As of 2014, the company covered 83,000 events annually from over 300 leagues and competitions. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = With clients like the NBA and Google, STATS is the coolest data company you've never heard of|url = http://www.builtinchicago.org/2014/02/25/clients-nba-and-google-stats-coolest-data-company-youve-never-heard|website = Built In Chicago|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref> In 2019, it merged with [[Perform Group|Perform Content]] following its sale to parent company Vista Equity Partners.\n\nStats Perform is headquartered in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], with other corporate offices in [[Limerick]], [[London]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Tokyo]], [[Beijing]], [[Bangalore]], [[Dubai]], [[The Hague]], [[Mexico City]], [[Barcelona]], [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]].\n\n==History==\nSTATS was founded in April 1981<ref name=\"timeline\">[http://biz.stats.com/timeline.asp STATS website: Timeline]</ref> by John Dewan,<ref>[http://www.actasports.com/detail.html?id=9780879463670 ACTA Sports: The Bill James Handbook 2009]</ref> who became the company's CEO. The company name is an acronym for \"Sports Team Analysis and Tracking Systems\". STATS was an outgrowth of the grassroots non-profit Project Scoresheet, a volunteer network created to collect [[sabermetrics|baseball statistics.]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = Keep Score, Project Scoresheet\u2013Style|url = https://www.safaribooksonline.com/library/view/baseball-hacks/0596009429/ch01s04.html|first = Safari Books|last = Online}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996 STATS and [[Motorola]] won on appeal a court case brought by the NBA. The case was barring STATS from distributing in-game information via a special wireless device created by Motorola.  The victory in this case has played a large part in other cases where professional sports leagues have tried to suppress live in-game information being distributed by other outlets.<ref>[http://legal.web.aol.com/decisions/dldecen/nba.html NBA Lawsuit - AOL.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702231859/http://legal.web.aol.com/decisions/dldecen/nba.html |date=July 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, STATS expanded to the [[National Football League]], the [[National Basketball Association]], the [[National Hockey League]], the [[Women's National Basketball Association]], in addition to other sports.<ref name=timeline />\n\n== Acquisitions ==\nSTATS operated as a private company from 1981 to 2000. STATS was purchased by [[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox Sports]] in 2000 and became a joint venture between [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] and the [[Associated Press]] in 2005.\n\nIn 2009, the company acquired the PA SportsTicker wire service from [[Press Association]], a UK news and information company. SportsTicker had previously been owned by [[ESPN]].<ref>http://www.crunchbase.com/company/pa-sportsticker</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Fox Sports and the AP sold STATS to [[Vista Equity Partners]], a private equity firm.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Ecker| first = Danny| title = Stats LLC sold to private-equity firm| work = Crain's Chicago Business| accessdate = 2015-04-26| date = 2014-05-15| url = http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20140515/BLOGS04/140519841/stats-llc-sold-to-private-equity-firm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FOX Sports and AP announce sale of sports data company STATS LLC|url = http://www.ap.org/Content/Press-Release/2014/FOX-Sports-and-The-Associated-Press-Announce-Sale-of-Sports-Data-Company-STATS-LLC|website = www.ap.org|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2014, the platform created over a billion articles and reports for customers such as [[The Associated Press]], [[Yahoo!]], and [[Comcast]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = STATS Gets Into the Robot News Game With Automated Insights Acquisition|url = http://chicagoinno.streetwise.co/2015/02/12/stats-acquires-automated-insights/|website = Chicago Inno|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref> In September 2014, STATS acquired Bloomberg Sports.\n\nIn early 2015, STATS acquired the wire service [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]] and Prozone. Vista Equity Partners also acquired [[Automated Insights]], a company involved in using [[natural-language generation]] based on [[big data]] (including in particular, generating wire reports on sporting events from raw statistics).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Stats LLC Makes Athlete Performance Outfit Prozone Its Latest Acquisition|work= SportsBusiness Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals |url = http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2015/05/05/Finance/Stats.aspx|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Vista Equity Partners announced its intent to acquire Perform Content, the former sports data subsidiary of [[Perform Group]], including units such as Omnisport, [[Opta Sports]], and RunningBall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/europe/2019/04/03/dazn-nears-entire-data-offload-to-vista-equity/|title=DAZN nears entire data offload to Vista Equity|date=2019-04-03|website=SBC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> The company was selling the property to focus more on its sports streaming service [[DAZN]]. It was stated that [[DAZN Group]] would retain a \"significant minority stake\" in the surviving entity, which was to focus strongly on the use of [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dazn-perform-stats-merge-streaming-business-vista-acquisition|title=DAZN Group to prioritise streaming business as Perform and STATS merge|website=SportsPro |access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dazn-len-blavatnik-perform-content|title=Report: DAZN owner planning split to increase focus on OTT platform|website=SportsPro|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/broadcasting/dazn-group-sells-perform/5138568.article|title=DAZN Group sells Perform|website=Broadcast|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> \n\nOn July 15, 2019, it was announced that the merged company would be known as Stats Perform, and operate under STATS CEO Carl Mergele. He stated that the company would \"[harness] the power of immense amounts of sports data with unparalleled AI technology\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/stats-perform-merger-vista-dazn-artificial-intelligence-data|title=STATS and Perform confirm merger|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/07/15/Stats.aspx|title=Stats, Perform Complete Merger, Creating New Data/AI Company|date=15 July 2019|publisher=Sports Business Daily|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\nSTATS provides several products to leagues, teams, and the media.\n\nThe X-Info system provides [[National Football League|NFL]], [[college football]] and [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] teams with detailed statistics and information to help them interpret the various metrics.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Football Is Closer to Becoming Moneyball Than You May Think (NWS)|url = http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/05/nfl-big-data.aspx|website = www.fool.com|accessdate = 2015-06-30|first = Jake|last = Mann}}</ref>\n\nTheir SportVU system uses an array of cameras and image processing software to provide real-time player tracking and ball positioning data, as well as statistical analysis of that data. SportVU is used by FIFA, UEFA and a host of flagship European soccer teams.<ref>{{Cite web|title = GOAL! Wait, was that in? How tech will answer the question at the World Cup|url = http://www.digitaltrends.com/sports/goal-wait-tech-will-answer-question-world-cup/|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nNearly every franchise in three of [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|North America's four major professional sports leagues]] (NFL, MLB, and NHL) uses products from STATS.<ref name=\"sporttechie.com\"/>\n\nWith the acquisition of The Sports Network, STATS took over publication of that company's NCAA [[NCAA Division I#Football Championship Subdivision|Division I FCS]] football poll.\n\n==See also==\n[[Elias Sports Bureau]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs = http://stats.nba.com/tracking/#!/player/\nhttp://www.fastcompany.com/most-innovative-companies/2014/stats\nhttp://www.fsta.org/?AwardWinners\nhttp://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/05/nfl-big-data.aspx}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.statsperform.com}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball statistics]]\n[[Category:Former News Corporation subsidiaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US sports technology and data company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Stats Perform\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founded = {{start date|1981|04|30}}\n| founder = John Dewan\n| hq_location = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Carl Mergele (CEO)\n| industry = Sports Technology and Data\n| products = Sports data, analytics and team tracking solutions\n| brands = Omnisports, [[Opta Sports]], [[Prozone Sports Ltd|Prozone]], [[TVTI]], [[Automated Insights]], [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]], [[BSports]]\n| services = \n| owner = [[golem]]\n| website = {{URL|statsperform.com}}\n| former_name = \n}}\n\n'''Stats Perform''' (formerly '''STATS LLC''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=739452|title=STATS LLC: Private Company Information|website=[[Bloomberg.com]]|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref> is a [[Chicago]]-based sports data and [[sports analytics|analytics]] company.\n\nThe company is involved in sports data collection and [[Predictive analytics|predictive analysis]], and maintains sports-oriented [[wire service]]s. The company has also been increasingly involved in [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]].<ref name=\"sporttechie.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sporttechie.com/the-evolution-of-stats-llc-and-its-place-in-the-sports-technology-landscape/|title=The Evolution of STATS LLC And Its Place In The Sports Technology Landscape|website=SportTechie|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Its clients include media outlets, sports leagues and teams, [[fantasy sports]] and [[sports betting]] services. As of 2014, the company covered 83,000 events annually from over 300 leagues and competitions. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = With clients like the NBA and Google, STATS is the coolest data company you've never heard of|url = http://www.builtinchicago.org/2014/02/25/clients-nba-and-google-stats-coolest-data-company-youve-never-heard|website = Built In Chicago|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref> In 2019, it merged with [[Perform Group|Perform Content]] following its sale to parent company Vista Equity Partners.\n\nStats Perform is headquartered in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], with other corporate offices in [[Limerick]], [[London]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Tokyo]], [[Beijing]], [[Bangalore]], [[Dubai]], [[The Hague]], [[Mexico City]], [[Barcelona]], [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]].\n\n==History==\nSTATS was founded in April 1981<ref name=\"timeline\">[http://biz.stats.com/timeline.asp STATS website: Timeline]</ref> by John Dewan,<ref>[http://www.actasports.com/detail.html?id=9780879463670 ACTA Sports: The Bill James Handbook 2009]</ref> who became the company's CEO. The company name is an acronym for \"Sports Team Analysis and Tracking Systems\". STATS was an outgrowth of the grassroots non-profit Project Scoresheet, a volunteer network created to collect [[sabermetrics|baseball statistics.]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = Keep Score, Project Scoresheet\u2013Style|url = https://www.safaribooksonline.com/library/view/baseball-hacks/0596009429/ch01s04.html|first = Safari Books|last = Online}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996 STATS and [[Motorola]] won on appeal a court case brought by the NBA. The case was barring STATS from distributing in-game information via a special wireless device created by Motorola.  The victory in this case has played a large part in other cases where professional sports leagues have tried to suppress live in-game information being distributed by other outlets.<ref>[http://legal.web.aol.com/decisions/dldecen/nba.html NBA Lawsuit - AOL.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702231859/http://legal.web.aol.com/decisions/dldecen/nba.html |date=July 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, STATS expanded to the [[National Football League]], the [[National Basketball Association]], the [[National Hockey League]], the [[Women's National Basketball Association]], in addition to other sports.<ref name=timeline />\n\n== Acquisitions ==\nSTATS operated as a private company from 1981 to 2000. STATS was purchased by [[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox Sports]] in 2000 and became a joint venture between [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] and the [[Associated Press]] in 2005.\n\nIn 2009, the company acquired the PA SportsTicker wire service from [[Press Association]], a UK news and information company. SportsTicker had previously been owned by [[ESPN]].<ref>http://www.crunchbase.com/company/pa-sportsticker</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Fox Sports and the AP sold STATS to [[Vista Equity Partners]], a private equity firm.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Ecker| first = Danny| title = Stats LLC sold to private-equity firm| work = Crain's Chicago Business| accessdate = 2015-04-26| date = 2014-05-15| url = http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20140515/BLOGS04/140519841/stats-llc-sold-to-private-equity-firm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FOX Sports and AP announce sale of sports data company STATS LLC|url = http://www.ap.org/Content/Press-Release/2014/FOX-Sports-and-The-Associated-Press-Announce-Sale-of-Sports-Data-Company-STATS-LLC|website = www.ap.org|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2014, the platform created over a billion articles and reports for customers such as [[The Associated Press]], [[Yahoo!]], and [[Comcast]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = STATS Gets Into the Robot News Game With Automated Insights Acquisition|url = http://chicagoinno.streetwise.co/2015/02/12/stats-acquires-automated-insights/|website = Chicago Inno|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref> In September 2014, STATS acquired Bloomberg Sports.\n\nIn early 2015, STATS acquired the wire service [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]] and Prozone. Vista Equity Partners also acquired [[Automated Insights]], a company involved in using [[natural-language generation]] based on [[big data]] (including in particular, generating wire reports on sporting events from raw statistics).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Stats LLC Makes Athlete Performance Outfit Prozone Its Latest Acquisition|work= SportsBusiness Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals |url = http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2015/05/05/Finance/Stats.aspx|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Vista Equity Partners announced its intent to acquire Perform Content, the former sports data subsidiary of [[Perform Group]], including units such as Omnisport, [[Opta Sports]], and RunningBall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/europe/2019/04/03/dazn-nears-entire-data-offload-to-vista-equity/|title=DAZN nears entire data offload to Vista Equity|date=2019-04-03|website=SBC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> The company was selling the property to focus more on its sports streaming service [[DAZN]]. It was stated that [[DAZN Group]] would retain a \"significant minority stake\" in the surviving entity, which was to focus strongly on the use of [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dazn-perform-stats-merge-streaming-business-vista-acquisition|title=DAZN Group to prioritise streaming business as Perform and STATS merge|website=SportsPro |access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dazn-len-blavatnik-perform-content|title=Report: DAZN owner planning split to increase focus on OTT platform|website=SportsPro|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/broadcasting/dazn-group-sells-perform/5138568.article|title=DAZN Group sells Perform|website=Broadcast|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> \n\nOn July 15, 2019, it was announced that the merged company would be known as Stats Perform, and operate under STATS CEO Carl Mergele. He stated that the company would \"[harness] the power of immense amounts of sports data with unparalleled AI technology\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/stats-perform-merger-vista-dazn-artificial-intelligence-data|title=STATS and Perform confirm merger|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/07/15/Stats.aspx|title=Stats, Perform Complete Merger, Creating New Data/AI Company|date=15 July 2019|publisher=Sports Business Daily|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\nSTATS provides several products to leagues, teams, and the media.\n\nThe X-Info system provides [[National Football League|NFL]], [[college football]] and [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] teams with detailed statistics and information to help them interpret the various metrics.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Football Is Closer to Becoming Moneyball Than You May Think (NWS)|url = http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/05/nfl-big-data.aspx|website = www.fool.com|accessdate = 2015-06-30|first = Jake|last = Mann}}</ref>\n\nTheir SportVU system uses an array of cameras and image processing software to provide real-time player tracking and ball positioning data, as well as statistical analysis of that data. SportVU is used by FIFA, UEFA and a host of flagship European soccer teams.<ref>{{Cite web|title = GOAL! Wait, was that in? How tech will answer the question at the World Cup|url = http://www.digitaltrends.com/sports/goal-wait-tech-will-answer-question-world-cup/|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nNearly every franchise in three of [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|North America's four major professional sports leagues]] (NFL, MLB, and NHL) uses products from STATS.<ref name=\"sporttechie.com\"/>\n\nWith the acquisition of The Sports Network, STATS took over publication of that company's NCAA [[NCAA Division I#Football Championship Subdivision|Division I FCS]] football poll.\n\n==See also==\n[[Elias Sports Bureau]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs = http://stats.nba.com/tracking/#!/player/\nhttp://www.fastcompany.com/most-innovative-companies/2014/stats\nhttp://www.fsta.org/?AwardWinners\nhttp://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/05/nfl-big-data.aspx}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.statsperform.com}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball statistics]]\n[[Category:Former News Corporation subsidiaries]]\n", "name_user": "Mmorrisoncce", "label": "safe", "comment": "Company owner", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stats_Perform"}
{"title_page": "Evelyn Guerrero", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Evelyn Guerrero\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|2|24}}\n|birth_place = [[East Los Angeles, California]], United States\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|othername =\n|occupation = [[Actor|Actress]]\n|yearsactive = 1969&ndash;1999\n|spouse = [[Pat Morita]] 1994&ndash;2005 (his death)\n|domesticpartner =\n|website =\n}}\n'''Evelyn Guerrero''' (born February 24, 1949) is a former American actress. She was married to actor [[Pat Morita]]. Guerrero starred in various movies and television series from 1969 to 1999. She first met Pat Morita when she was 15.<ref name=\"TCM_biography\" /> They met again almost 30 years later and were married in 1994. Retired from acting, Guerrero and Morita lived in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] following their marriage.\n\nShe is best known for portraying \"Donna\" in three [[Cheech and Chong]] movies. In 1980, Guerrero became the first Latina to pose in \"Playboy\" magazine.<ref name=\"TCM_biography\">{{cite web |title=Biography - Evelyn Guerrero/ |url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/77746%7C0/Evelyn-Guerrero/ |website=tcm.com |publisher=TCM |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |ref=TCM-Evelyn_Guerrero}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 she was interviewed by Natural Habitat Podcast<ref name=\"NHP#078\">{{cite web |title=NHP#078 - Evelyn Guerrero-Morita |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQf8F25XSbI |website=youtube |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |ref=NHP#078 - Evelyn Guerrero-Morita}}</ref> about her life, her involvement with Cheech and Chong movies, meeting [[Timothy Leary]] and about her late husband, Pat Morita.\n\n==Filmography==\n<!-- Please note: \"rowspan\" breaks table sortability. -->\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1969\n|''Wild Wheels''\n|Sissy\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''{{sortname|The|Toolbox Murders}}''\n|Maria\n|\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[She Came to the Valley]]''\n|Connie\n|\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Cheech and Chong's Next Movie]]''\n|Donna\n|\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Nice Dreams]]''\n|Donna\n|\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Things Are Tough All Over]]''\n|Donna\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Alligator II: The Mutation]]''\n|Elena\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Blood In Blood Out]]''\n|Luisa\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''...And the Earth Did Not Swallow Him''\n|Lupita\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Inferno (1999 film)|Inferno]]''\n|Bertie Early\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]''\n|Ziba\n|\"Tender Soldier\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''{{sortname|The|Quest|The Quest (1976 TV series)}}''\n|Delores\n|\"Shanklin\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''{{sortname|The|Return of Frank Cannon|nolink=1}}''\n|Inez\n|TV film\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Whiz Kids (TV series)|Whiz Kids]]''\n|Dorita\n|\"Watch Out!\"\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Hill Street Blues]]''\n|Mrs. Pinzon\n|\"The Virgin and the Turkey\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''{{sortname|The|Colbys}}''\n|Jane\n|\"A Family Affair\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''\n|Rosie\n|\"Overture\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''\n|Young Female Ensign\n|\"[[Encounter at Farpoint]]\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[I Married Dora]]''\n|Marisol\n|\"My Parents Are Coming\", \"Club Montez\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Simon & Simon]]''\n|D.A. Anita Sanchez\n|\"New Cop in Town\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''{{sortname|The|Facts of Life|The Facts of Life (TV series)}}''\n|Mrs. Martinez\n|\"Adventures in Baileysitting\"\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[CBS Summer Playhouse]]''\n|Lupe Cordero\n|\"Fort Figueroa\"\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|Hunter]]''\n|Santana\n|\"Dead on Target: Part 1\"\n|-\n|1989\u201390\n|''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''\n|Nancy\n|\"Sunset, Sunrise\", \"A Tale of Two Cities\", \"The Odessa File\"\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Dynasty: The Reunion]]''\n|Maid\n|\"1.1\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0346186}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guerrero, Evelyn}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n\n\n{{StarTrek-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Evelyn Guerrero\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|2|24}}\n|birth_place = [[East Los Angeles, California]], United States\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|othername =\n|occupation = [[Actor|Actress]]\n|yearsactive = 1969&ndash;1999\n|spouse = [[Pat Morita]] 1994&ndash;2005 (his death)\n|domesticpartner =\n|website =\n}}\n'''Evelyn Guerrero''' (born February 24, 1949) is a former American actress. She was married to actor [[Pat Morita]]. Guerrero starred in various movies and television series from 1969 to 1999. She first met Pat Morita when she was 15.<ref name=\"TCM_biography\" /> They met again almost 30 years later and were married in 1994. Retired from acting, Guerrero and Morita lived in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] following their marriage.\n\nShe is best known for portraying \"Donna\" in three [[Cheech and Chong]] movies. In 1980, Guerrero became the first Latina to pose in \"Playboy\" magazine.<ref name=\"TCM_biography\">{{cite web |title=Biography - Evelyn Guerrero/ |url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/77746%7C0/Evelyn-Guerrero/ |website=http://www.tcm.com |publisher=TCM |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |ref=TCM-Evelyn_Guerrero}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 she was interviewed by Natural Habitat Podcast<ref name=\"NHP#078\">{{cite web |title=NHP#078 - Evelyn Guerrero-Morita |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQf8F25XSbI |website=youtube |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |ref=NHP#078 - Evelyn Guerrero-Morita}}</ref> about her life, her involvement with Cheech and Chong movies, meeting [[Timothy Leary]] and about her late husband, Pat Morita.\n\n==Filmography==\n<!-- Please note: \"rowspan\" breaks table sortability. -->\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1969\n|''Wild Wheels''\n|Sissy\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''{{sortname|The|Toolbox Murders}}''\n|Maria\n|\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[She Came to the Valley]]''\n|Connie\n|\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Cheech and Chong's Next Movie]]''\n|Donna\n|\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Nice Dreams]]''\n|Donna\n|\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Things Are Tough All Over]]''\n|Donna\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Alligator II: The Mutation]]''\n|Elena\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Blood In Blood Out]]''\n|Luisa\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''...And the Earth Did Not Swallow Him''\n|Lupita\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Inferno (1999 film)|Inferno]]''\n|Bertie Early\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]''\n|Ziba\n|\"Tender Soldier\"\n|-\n|1976\n|''{{sortname|The|Quest|The Quest (1976 TV series)}}''\n|Delores\n|\"Shanklin\"\n|-\n|1980\n|''{{sortname|The|Return of Frank Cannon|nolink=1}}''\n|Inez\n|TV film\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Whiz Kids (TV series)|Whiz Kids]]''\n|Dorita\n|\"Watch Out!\"\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Hill Street Blues]]''\n|Mrs. Pinzon\n|\"The Virgin and the Turkey\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''{{sortname|The|Colbys}}''\n|Jane\n|\"A Family Affair\"\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''\n|Rosie\n|\"Overture\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''\n|Young Female Ensign\n|\"[[Encounter at Farpoint]]\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[I Married Dora]]''\n|Marisol\n|\"My Parents Are Coming\", \"Club Montez\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Simon & Simon]]''\n|D.A. Anita Sanchez\n|\"New Cop in Town\"\n|-\n|1987\n|''{{sortname|The|Facts of Life|The Facts of Life (TV series)}}''\n|Mrs. Martinez\n|\"Adventures in Baileysitting\"\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[CBS Summer Playhouse]]''\n|Lupe Cordero\n|\"Fort Figueroa\"\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|Hunter]]''\n|Santana\n|\"Dead on Target: Part 1\"\n|-\n|1989\u201390\n|''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''\n|Nancy\n|\"Sunset, Sunrise\", \"A Tale of Two Cities\", \"The Odessa File\"\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Dynasty: The Reunion]]''\n|Maid\n|\"1.1\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0346186}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guerrero, Evelyn}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n\n\n{{StarTrek-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=http://www. \u2192 website=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evelyn_Guerrero"}
{"title_page": "My Prerogative", "text_new": "{{short description|1988 single by Bobby Brown}}\n{{for|the Britney Spears album|Greatest Hits: My Prerogative}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Prerogative\n| cover      = MyPrerogative-BBrown.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bobby Brown]]\n| album      = [[Don't Be Cruel (album)|Don't Be Cruel]]\n| released   = October 11, 1988\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Gramophone record|7\"]]|[[12-inch single|12\"]]|[[CD single|CD]]}}\n| recorded   = April 1988\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[New jack swing]]\n| length     = 4:51<br>4:25 {{small|(single version)}}\n| label      = [[MCA Records|MCA]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Bobby Brown]]|Gene Griffin<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">James Salazar - Don't Be Cruel (LP liner notes). MCA Records. MCA-42185</ref>}}\n| producer   = Gene Griffin<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n| prev_title = [[Don't Be Cruel (Bobby Brown song)|Don't Be Cruel]]\n| prev_year  = 1988\n| next_title = [[Roni (song)|Roni]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|5cDLZqe735k|\"My Prerogative\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''My Prerogative'''\" is a song by American singer [[Bobby Brown]] from his second [[studio album]] ''[[Don't Be Cruel (album)|Don't Be Cruel]]'' (1988). It was released on October 11, 1988 as the second single from the album. After recording sessions for the album were completed, Brown and producer Gene Griffin traveled to [[New York City]], since he felt something was \"missing\" from the record. \"My Prerogative\" was written by Brown as a response to the criticism he received for his departure from [[New Edition]]. He explained the song was about making decisions in one's life and not caring about other people's judgment. \"My Prerogative\" is often considered a [[new jack swing]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nThe song was positively received by critics and was nominated for a [[30th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] in the category of Best R&B Urban Contemporary Single. It was also commercially successful, reaching number one in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] and [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] charts. \"My Prerogative\" also reached top ten positions in many countries, such as Ireland, New Zealand, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom. The music video for the song features Brown performing the song on stage with his band and dancers. The song was also performed at most of his concerts, usually as the last song of the set list. On the February 4, 1989 performance at [[Madison Square Garden]], he was joined on stage by many popular [[rapping|rap]] artists and producers of the time.\n\n\"My Prerogative\" has been covered and sampled by a number of artists from different genres, including [[Britney Spears]]. She released her cover in her first compilation, ''[[Greatest Hits: My Prerogative]]'' (2004). The cover was produced by [[Bloodshy & Avant]] and was noted for aptly referring to Spears's relationship with the media at the time. Although the song only appeared in component charts in the United States, Spears's cover surpassed Brown's version worldwide, peaking at the top of the charts in Finland, Ireland, Italy and Norway and reaching the top ten in another fourteen countries.<ref name=ultratop /><ref name=ultratopbrit />\n\n==Background==\nBrown had already completed recording sessions for ''Don't Be Cruel'' in [[Los Angeles, California]], but felt something was missing in the record. He said, \"I felt my album was lacking a strong, aggressive song and I thought, 'Where better than [[New York City|New York]] to come up with it'\". He traveled to New York, met with [[Teddy Riley]] - who presented him with the initial beat.<ref name=hour>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lyIiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fXQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3447,2939149|title=Bobby Brown takes his prerogative|date=1989-03-17|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Italie|first=Hillel|work=[[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]]}}</ref> \"My Prerogative\" was written and co-produced by Brown and Griffin. It was [[sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] at Axis Studios and [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] at Soundworks, in New York. The track was [[audio mastering|mastered]] at Future Disc Systems in [[Hollywood, California]].<ref>''[[Don't Be Cruel]]'' liner notes. [[MCA Records]] (1988)</ref> During an interview with ''[[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]]'' on March 17, 1989, Brown explained the theme behind the song, saying, \"A lot of things had been said about Bobby Brown, why was he doing this [a solo career]. It's my way of expressing to people it's your prerogative to do as you want, but make sure what you do is the right thing\".<ref name=hour /> A CD single of remixes by Joe T. Vannelli was released on October 13, 1995.<ref name=remix />\n\n==Composition==\n{{listen\n | filename    = Bobby brown - my prerogative.ogg\n | format      = [[Ogg]]\n | title       = \"My Prerogative\"\n | description = A 29 second sample of Bobby Brown's \"My Prerogative\", where the [[chorus effect|chorus]] is played with strong background vocals.\n}}\n\"My Prerogative\" is considered a [[new jack swing]] anthem, that merges [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] beats with elements of [[synthpop]] and [[soul music|soul]].<ref name=finally>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,274879,00.html|title=Finally|date=1999-03-26|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Diehl|first=Matt|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> It features a triplet swing in the [[sixteenth note]], as included in many of Riley's productions.<ref name=\"blue\">{{harvnb|Ripani|2006|p=131}}</ref> Jake Brown said in his book ''Your body's calling me: music, love, sex & money'' (2003), that like most new jack swing songs from the late 1980s, it was composed by \"punchy, street-savvy beats, with sexually energetic melodies and [[pop music|poppy]] choruses\".<ref name=\"jackswing\">{{harvnb|Brown|2003|p=20}}</ref> The [[bassline]] of the track was described by Cam'Ron Davis of ''[[CMJ New Music Monthly]]'' as \"truly sinister\".<ref name=cmj>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2CoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA66#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=Bobby Brown|date=March 2003|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Davis|first=Cam'Ron|work=[[CMJ New Music Monthly]]}}</ref> According to the sheet music published at Musicnotes.com by [[EMI Music Publishing]], the song is composed in the key of [[A minor]], with a [[tempo (music)|tempo]] of 120 [[beats per minute]]. Brown's vocal range spans from the high-note of [[C major|C<sub>4</sub>]] to [[A major|A<sub>5</sub>]].<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web|title=Bobby Brown \u2013 My Prerogative \u2013 Sheet Music |publisher=MusicNotes.com [[EMI Music Publishing]] |url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0064933 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108180125/https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0064933 |archivedate=2009-01-08 |accessdate=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nBarry Michael Cooper of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' said \"My Prerogative\" \"sounds like gin-drenched, [[Roaring Twenties]] swing\".<ref name=spin>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oyYjDeNc_AC&pg=PA42#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=Paid in Full|date=December 1988|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Cooper|first=Barry Michael|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref> Arion Berger of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called it \"a grumpy and undeniably adult dance hit\".<ref name=nkotb>{{cite magazine|url=|title=New Kids on the Block : Step by Step : Music Reviews|date=1990-08-09|work=[[Rolling Stone]] |last=Berger|first=Arion|ref=harv}}</ref> \"My Prerogative\" was nominated for at the [[1989 Soul Train Music Awards|3th Soul Train Music Awards]] in the category of Best R&B Urban Contemporary Single by a Male, but lost to [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\".<ref name=\"grammy\">{{harvnb|Campbell|1993|p=263}}</ref> The following year, ''Spin'' listed the song at number 72 on the \"100 Greatest Singles of All Time\" list.<ref name=spinsingles>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h-bxxO5B-xsC&pg=PA116|title=100 Greatest Singles of All Time|date=April 1989|accessdate=2010-03-13 |work=Spin}}</ref> It ranked at number 98 on [[VH1]]'s \"100 Greatest Songs of the 80's\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2006/vh180s2.htm|title=VH1: 100 Greatest Songs of the 80's: 51-100|year=2006|accessdate=|publisher=[[VH1]]}}</ref> The track is often referred to as Brown's [[signature song]].<ref name=ebony>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T9cDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA51-IA10#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=The 55 Most Intriguing Blacks of 2000|date=November 2000|accessdate=2010-03-13 |work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]}}</ref>\n\n\"My Prerogative\" debuted on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100 during the week of October 29, 1988 at number 61.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1988-10-29/hot-100|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week of October 29, 1988|date=1988-10-29|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> The following week, it climbed 16 positions to number 45.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1988-11-05/hot-100|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week of November 5, 1988|date=1988-11-05|work=Billboard |accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> On January 14, 1989, it peaked at the top position of the chart. The song also peaked at number one in [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] and at number seven in [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name=bbcharts>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=bobby brown|chart=all}}|title=My Prerogative - Bobby Brown Billboard charts|date=|work=Billboard|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> It was certified [[RIAA certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for sales over 500,000 copies.<ref name=riaacerti>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Searchable Database - RIAA - Bobby Brown |date=2010-01-05 |accessdate=2010-03-17 |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=2007-06-26}}</ref> In Canada, the song debuted on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Singles Chart at position 98, on the issue dated December 23, 1989.<ref name=rpm>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6684&volume=51&issue=8&issue_dt=December%2023%201989&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles - Volume 51, No. 8, December 23, 1988|date=1989-12-23|publisher=RPM Music Publications Ltd|accessdate=2010-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013154005/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6684&volume=51&issue=8&issue_dt=December%2023%201989&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 13, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, \"My Prerogative\" debuted at number 87 on December 10, 1988. On February 18, 1989, the song peaked at number six and stayed in the position for two weeks.<ref name=uk>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/I%20Second%20That%20Emotion|title=The Official Charts Company - Bobby Brown - My Prerogative|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Following the release of the remixes single on October 14, 1995, \"My Prerogative\" re-entered the UK charts at number 17, and stayed on the chart for two weeks.<ref name=remix /> By 17 October 2015, it had sold 275,000 units in the country.<ref name=sale2015>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ask-official-charts-your-questions-on-demi-selena-britney-and-more-answered__11053/|title=Ask Official Charts: Your questions on Demi, Selena, Britney and more answered|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=2015-10-17|accessdate=2015-10-17|publisher=The Official Charts Company}}</ref> Across Europe, the song reached the top ten in Ireland and the Netherlands,<ref name=ultratop>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Bobby+Brown&titel=My+Prerogative&cat=s|title=Bobby Brown - My Prerogative (song) |year=1989|publisher=[[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref><ref name=ire>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |title=The Irish Charts |date=1989-02-09 |publisher=[[Irish Singles Chart]]. [[Irish Recorded Music Association]] |accessdate=2010-03-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602061251/http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |archivedate=2009-06-02}}</ref> and the top 20 in Germany and Sweden.<ref name=ultratop /><ref name=ger>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicinfonet.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/BROWN%2CBOBBY/single|title=Brown, Bobby|date=1989-06-18|publisher=[[Media Control Charts]]. musicline.de|accessdate=2010-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719065005/http://www.musicinfonet.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/BROWN,BOBBY/single|archive-date=2011-07-19|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Australia and New Zealand, the track peaked at number 40 and number three, respectively.<ref name=ultratop />\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:My Prerogative Bobby Brown.JPG|thumb|Brown performing in a scene of the music video.|alt=An African American man. He is surrounded by two women playing instruments. He is wearing a black suit and a headset, while performing on a stage with the women. The women are wearing black lace outfits.]]\nThe [[music video]] for \"My Prerogative\" was directed by [[Alek Keshishian]].<ref name=alek>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YNwrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=imQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1584,1543730|title='Truth or Dare' Exhausts Director|date=1991-05-14|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Italie|first=Hillel|work=Kentucky New Era}}</ref> It begins with Brown driving a car while his musicians start to perform the song on stage in front of a large crowd. Shortly after, he descends to the stage in an elevator, wearing a black [[jumpsuit]] and a headset. He dances flanked by two women, one of them playing a [[keytar]].<ref name=cmj />\n\nJ. D. Considine of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote in the review of ''[[Bobby (Bobby Brown album)|Bobby]]'' (1992), \"As anyone who saw him swagger through the videos for 'My Prerogative' and '[[Every Little Step]]' can attest, Brown had a phenomenal ability to convey a sense of street toughness that was utterly without malice or menace, making him credible and likable\".<ref name=bobbyreview>{{cite magazine|url=|title=Bobby Brown : Bobby : Music Reviews|date=1992-09-12|work=[[Rolling Stone]] |last=Considine|first=J. D. |ref=harv}}</ref> The music video was nominated at the [[1989 MTV Video Music Awards]] for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Stage Performance|Best Stage Performance in a Video]], but lost to the music video of [[Living Colour]]'s \"[[Cult of Personality (song)|Cult of Personality]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/mtvvma/stage.htm|title=MTV Video Music Awards History: Best Stage Performance Video|year=1984|publisher=[[VH1]]}}</ref> It also charted at number nine on ''RPM'' video chart on July 21, 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7954&volume=52&issue=10&issue_dt=July%2021%201990&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Video - Volume 52, No. 10, July 21, 1990|date=1990-07-21|work=RPM|publisher=RPM Music Publications Ltd|accessdate=2010-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230090117/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7954&volume=52&issue=10&issue_dt=July%2021%201990&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=December 30, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n\"My Prerogative\" was performed during his tour in promotion for ''Don't Be Cruel'' as the last song of the night. Brown usually performed it wearing a black outfit, flanked with two male dancers wearing white clothes.<ref name=toledo>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rw0VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_gIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7114,457260|title=Bobby Brown puts moves on Toledo|date=1989-05-10|accessdate=2010-03-13|last=Kisiel|first=Ralph|work=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]]}}</ref> On the February 4, 1989, show at Madison Square Garden in New York City, Brown wore a red boxing robe with the words \"King of the Stage\" printed on the back. During the performance, [[Joseph Simmons]] of [[Run-DMC]], [[LL Cool J]] and [[Heavy D]] joined him onstage and [[freestyle rap]]ped. [[Eric B.]], [[KRS-One]], [[L. A. Reid]], [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] and Teddy Riley also joined him onstage, with the latter performing a [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] solo. Peter Watrous of ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented that, \"The communal scene on stage mirrored the feeling in the audience; everybody seemed aware that this was a generation that had rewritten the rules of pop entertainment, and was justifiably proud of its achievement\".<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/06/arts/review-music-bobby-brown-holds-a-garden-party.html?pagewanted=1|title=Review/Music; Bobby Brown Holds a Garden Party|date=1989-02-06|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Watrous|first=Peter|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Brown also performed the song at the 1997 Home Again Tour with [[New Edition]], during the second portion of the show in which he performed hits from his solo career.<ref name=newedition>{{cite magazine |url=|title=New Edition: Rolling Stone|date=1997-01-13|work=Rolling Stone|ref=harv}}</ref> On November 10, 2005, he performed the song for the first time in eight years at a concert at [[House of Blues]] in [[Atlantic City]]. He wore a white suit and matching hat, and sang it as the last song of the evening.<ref name=atlantic>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1513550/20051111/brown_bobby.jhtml|title=Ladies' Man Reborn: Bobby Brown Back In Shape At Atlantic City Gig|date=2005-11-11|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Reid|first=Shaheem|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[MTV Networks]]}}</ref> On January 17, 2006, he performed it at a New Edition show in Atlantic City's [[Trump Taj Mahal]]. During the performance, he tore open his orange dress shirt, singing bare-chested with a tie and a fur coat on.<ref name=atlantic2>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1520836/20060117/new_edition.jhtml|title=New Edition Reuniting Again \u2014 And This Time, Bobby's On Board| date=2007-01-17|accessdate=2010-03-13| last=Reid|first=Shaheem|publisher=MTV}}</ref> Brown performed the song during his 2007 July shows in Australia.<ref name=aus>{{cite news|url=http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=2326|title=Bobby Brown Brings Greatest Hits to Australia|date=2007-07-19|accessdate=2010-03-13|last=Tijs|first=Andrew|publisher=undercover.com.au. Cashmere Media Pty Ltd|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830174838/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=2326|archivedate=2007-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''CD single'''\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Edit) \u2013 3:30\n#\"Girl Next Door\" (Extended version) \u2013 6:31\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Extended remix) \u2013 8:03\n\n*'''7\" single'''\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Edit) \u2013 3:30\n#\"Girl Next Door\" \u2013 4:06\n\n*'''12\" single'''\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Extended remix) \u2013 8:00\n#\"Girl Next Door\" (Extended version) \u2013 6:30\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Instrumental) \u2013 5:18\n{{col-2}}\n*'''12\" remix'''\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Extended remix) \u2013 8:00\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Radio edit) \u2013 5:35\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Instrumental) \u2013 5:18\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Dub) \u2013 5:52\n\n*'''1995 remix'''\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Joe T. Vannelli Radio Mix) \u2013 3:55\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Joe T. Vannelli Corvette Mix) \u2013 6:30\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Joe T. Vannelli Light Mix) \u2013 8:23\n#\"My Prerogative\" (Joe T. Vannelli Dubby Mix) \u2013 9:34\n#\"My Prerogative\" \u2013 4:49\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n* [[Bobby Brown]] \u2013 [[lead vocals]], songwriting, [[record producer|co-production]]\n* Gene Griffin \u2013 songwriting, [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]], co-production\n* [[Teddy Riley]] \u2013 background vocals, keyboards, mixing\n* Dennis Mitchell \u2013 engineering, mixing, [[sound recording and reproduction|recording]]\n* Jim Hanneman \u2013 engineering, mixing, recording\n* [[Wreckx-n-Effect|Markell Riley]] \u2013 [[programming (music)|drum programming]]\n* [[Aaron Hall (singer)|Aaron Hall]] \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Bernard Belle]] \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Today (band)|Lee Drakeford]] \u2013 background vocals\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1988\u201389)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| [[Kent Music Report|Australian Kent Music Report]]<ref name=ultratop />\n| align=\"center\"|40\n|-\n| Canada Top Singles ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]<ref>[http://rpmimages.3345.ca/pdfs/Volume+49-No.+14-January+20+-+February+4%2C+1989.pdf Canada Top Singles peak]</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n| [[MegaCharts|Dutch Mega Top 50]]<ref name=ultratop />\n| align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n| [[Media Control Charts|German Singles Chart]]<ref name=ger />\n| align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n| [[Irish Recorded Music Association|Irish Singles Chart]]<ref name=ire />\n| align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n| [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Singles Chart]]<ref name=ultratop />\n| align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n| [[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Singles Chart]]<ref name=ultratop />\n| align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKchartstats|6|artist=Bobby Brown}}\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=bbcharts />\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Black Singles]]<ref name=bbcharts />\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]]<ref name=bbcharts />\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n!align=\"center\"|Chart (1995)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak <br /> position\n|-\n| UK Singles Chart<ref name=remix>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/My%20Prerogative%20%7B1995%7D|title=The Official Charts Company - Bobby Brown - My Prerogative (1995)|year=1995|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2011-04-28}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1989)\n! Rank\n|-\n| [[RPM (magazine)|Canadian ''RPM'' Singles Chart]]<ref name=rpm />\n| align=\"center\"|98\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1989.php |title=Billboard Top 100 - 1989 |accessdate=2010-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125092422/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1989.php |archivedate=2010-01-25}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n|}\n\n===All-time charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1958-2018)\n! Position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100-60th-anniversary|title=Billboard Hot 100 60th Anniversary Interactive Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|507\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|artist=Bobby Brown|title=My Prerogative|certyear=1989|award=Gold|access-date=June 2, 2015}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Britney Spears version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Prerogative\n| cover      = BSMyPrerogative.jpg\n| alt        = Spears holding a microphone in her hand next to her head, while looking towards the left side of the picture.\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Britney Spears]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits: My Prerogative]]\n| B-side     = {{hlist|\"[[I've Just Begun (Having My Fun)]]\"|\"Chris Cox Megamix\"}}\n| released   = September 21, 2004\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Twelve-inch single|12\u201d]]|[[DVD]]|[[music download|digital download]]|}}\n| recorded   = May 2004\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=33}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Bobby Brown]]|Gene Griffin<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Bobby Brown - Don't Be Cruel (LP liner notes). MCA Records. MCA-42185</ref>|[[Teddy Riley]]}}\n| producer   = [[Bloodshy & Avant]]\n| prev_title = [[Outrageous (song)|Outrageous]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[Do Somethin']]\n| next_year  = 2005\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|dIOH8Trfas4|\"My Prerogative\"}}}}\n}}\n\n===Background and composition===\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Britney spears - my prerogative.ogg|title=\"My Prerogative\"|description=A 21 second sample of \"My Prerogative\", in which Spears sings over a background of synthesizers.}}\nIn 2004, [[Britney Spears]] recorded a cover of \"My Prerogative\" with Swedish production team [[Bloodshy & Avant]], who produced her single \"[[Toxic (song)|Toxic]]\" from her fourth studio album, ''[[In the Zone]]'' (2003). Bloodshy & Avant recorded the song at Murlyn Studios in [[Stockholm, Sweden]]. Spears recorded the vocals at Teldex Studios in [[Berlin, Germany]] during the European leg of her tour \"[[The Onyx Hotel Tour]]\" in 2004.<ref>''[[Greatest Hits: My Prerogative]]'' liner notes. [[Jive Records]] (2004)</ref> On August 13, 2004, Spears's label [[Jive Records]] announced through a press release that she had covered the song and was planning to release it on her first greatest hits compilation, titled ''[[Greatest Hits: My Prerogative]]''. The song was set to premiere on radio stations on September 14, 2004,<ref name=press>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490190/20040813/spears_britney.jhtml?headlines=true|title=Britney Covers Bobby Brown's 'My Prerogative' For Forthcoming LP|date=2004-08-13|accessdate=2010-03-14| last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|publisher=MTV}}</ref> however, it leaked in the Real Tapemasters Inc.'s [[mixtape]] ''The Future of R&B'' on September 10, 2004.<ref name=mixtape>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490900/20040910/spears_britney.jhtml|title=Britney's 'Prerogative' Hits The Streets \u2014 On A Mixtape|date=2004-09-10|accessdate=2010-03-14| last=Reid|first=Shaheem|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n\nThe song is set in [[common time]] and has a moderate [[tempo]] of 100 beats per minute. It is written in the key of [[B-flat minor|B\u266d minor]] and follows the chord progression of Bbm\u2013F\u2013Bbm throughout, making it in the [[harmonic minor]] scale.<ref>{{cite web|title= Britney Spears - My Prerogative (Digital Sheet Music)|publisher= Musicnotes, Inc.|url= https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0048539 |accessdate= March 23, 2018}}</ref> Spears' cover of \"My Prerogative\" is musically different from its original version, with the [[bass guitar|bass]] and [[new jack swing]] sound replaced with a [[synthpop]] sound, [[synthesizer]]s and elements typical of Bloodshy & Avant productions.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jon |last= O'Brien |title= Britney Spears \u2013 My Prerogative |website= AllMusic |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/my-prerogative-mw0000769213 |accessdate= July 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=press /><ref name=mixtape /> It was noted by Christy Lemire of [[msnbc.com]] that the cover also contains elements of [[Bollywood songs|Bollywood music]].<ref name=msnbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/britney-s-entirely-premature-greatest-hits-wbna6399700|title=Britney\u2019s entirely premature greatest hits|date=2004-11-09|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Lemire|first=Christy|publisher=Today.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the song, Spears says in a breathy voice the lines \"People can take everything away from you / But they can never take away your truth / But the question is, can you handle mine?\". The rest of the lyrics do not deviate much from the original version, instead they are changed to fit a woman's perspective.<ref name=mixtape /> Jennifer Vineyard of [[MTV]] commented the cover could be interpreted as a statement on Spears's life and the media reaction to some of her decisions at the time, including her engagement to American dancer [[Kevin Federline]].<ref name=press />\n\n===Reception===\nThe cover received mixed to negative reviews from contemporary critics. Stephen Thomas Erlewine of [[Allmusic]] called the cover \"a useless remake, which seems to exist solely for its video\".<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r716835|pure_url=yes}}|title=((( Greatest Hits: My Prerogative > Review )))|year=2004|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|website=Allmusic}}</ref> Spence D. of [[IGN]] said that the lyrics fit perfectly with Spears's relationship with the media at the time. He also added, \"As for her interpretation, it's an interesting chameleonic diversion that comes off like a [[mashup (music)|mash-up]] between vintage [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]-styled production, [[Cameo (band)|Cameo]] swagger, and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] sultriness, but never seems to capture the gloss and glory of any of the aforementioned influences\".<ref name=ign>{{cite news|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/566/566584p3.html|title=Britney Spears Greatest Hits: My Prerogative|date=2004-11-16|accessdate=2010-03-19|last=D.|first=Spence|publisher=[[IGN]]. [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622004830/http://music.ign.com/articles/566/566584p3.html|archivedate=2011-06-22}}</ref> Christy Lemire of msnbc.com called it \"utterly unnecessary\".<ref name=msnbc /> Louis Pattison of the ''[[New Musical Express]]'' commented that \"judging by the fuck-you sentiments\" of the cover, Spears liked to play the role of \"[the] pop brat careering off the rails\".<ref name=nme>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/britney-spears/7567|title=Spears, Britney : Greatest Hits: My Prerogative|date=2004-12-08|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Pattison|first=Louis|work=[[New Musical Express]]}}</ref> Sarah Hepola of [[Salon.com]] wrote in an article about contemporary [[teen idol]]s that the cover \"became an anthem for teen-idol rebellion\".<ref name=salon>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/feature/2009/03/26/zac_efron/print.html |title=Zac Efron and the twilight of the teen idol |date=2009-03-29 |accessdate=2010-03-19 |last=Hepola |first=Sarah |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]. Salon Media Group |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605062334/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/feature/2009/03/26/zac_efron/print.html |archivedate=2011-06-05}}</ref> American director [[Quentin Tarantino]] included the song in a playlist that inspired him during production of his 2009 film ''[[Inglourious Basterds]]''.<ref name=tarantino>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1619330/story.jhtml|title='Inglourious Basterds' Director Quentin Tarantino Inspired By Britney Spears?|date=2009-08-24|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, \"My Prerogative\" failed to chart on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] but charted in ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Top 40 Tracks]] and [[Mainstream Top 40]] at numbers 22 and 34, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p320976|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic ((( Britney Spears > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles )))|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> \"My Prerogative\" has sold 374,000 paid digital downloads in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/473716/britney-spears-lead-singles-track-by-track|title=Britney Spears' Lead Singles, Track-By-Track|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=2011-01-10|accessdate=2011-01-17|work=Billboard}}</ref> On November 15, 2004, the song debuted at the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]] at number seven.<ref name=ausbrit>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/australia_singles_top_50/2004/48|title=Australia Singles Top 50|publisher=acharts.us|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> It received a gold certification by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for shipments over 35,000 units.<ref name=ariacertification>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2004.htm |title=ARIA Charts&nbsp;\u2014 Accreditations \u2013 2004 Singles |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association |accessdate=2010-05-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061013053032/http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2004.htm |archivedate=2006-10-13}}</ref> The same week, it debuted at number seventeen in New Zealand.<ref name=newze>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/nz_singles_top_40/2004/47|title=New Zealand Top 40|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]]. acharts.us|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> On November 7, 2004, the song debuted at number three in the United Kingdom, during a competitive week of new releases, only surpassed by [[Eminem]]'s \"[[Just Lose It]]\" and [[Destiny's Child]]'s \"[[Lose My Breath]]\".<ref name=ukbrit>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/65740/eminem-sidesteps-destiny-spears-on-uk-chart|title=Eminem Sidesteps Destiny, Spears On U.K. Chart|year=2004|last=Reporter|first=Billboard|work=Billboard|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> According to [[Official Charts Company]], the song has sold 130,000 copies there.<ref name=sale2015 /> The song also reached success throughout Europe, peaking at number one in Finland, Ireland, Italy and Norway, number two in Spain and number three in Belgium (Flanders and Wallonia), Denmark and Germany.<ref name=ultratopbrit>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Britney+Spears&titel=My+Prerogative&cat=s|title=Britney Spears - My Prerogative (song) |year=2004|publisher=[[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref><ref name=achartsbrit>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/1813|title=Britney Spears - My Prerogative|year=2004|work=|publisher=acharts.us|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> It also reached top ten positions in Austria, Czech Republic, Sweden, Switzerland and the Netherlands.<ref name=ultratopbrit />\n\n===Music video===\n[[File:My Prerogative-Britney Spears music video.jpg|thumb|Spears dancing over a Porsche inside a pool at the beginning of the music video.|alt=Image of a blond woman. She is sitting over a white sports car, that is inside a pool. She is wet and wears a black dress. The pool is illuminated from above. She is looking up towards the camera.]]\nThe music video for \"My Prerogative\" was filmed in August 2004 at [[Canfield-Moreno Estate|The Paramour Mansion]] in [[Silver Lake, Los Angeles]] and was directed by [[Jake Nava]].<ref name=paramour>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W2IEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=The Next Wave|date=January 2005|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Coleridge|first=Daniel R.|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|publisher=[[Aaron Hicklin]]}}</ref><ref name=jake>{{cite news|url=http://www.britney.com/us/blog/earlier-filming-date-scheduled-britney-if-u-seek-amy-music-video-shoot |title=Earlier Filming Date Scheduled For Britney If U Seek Amy Music Video Shoot |date=2009-02-04 |accessdate=2010-03-19 |last=Staff |first=Reporter |publisher=Britney.com. [[RCA/Jive Label Group]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725080452/http://www.britney.com/us/blog/earlier-filming-date-scheduled-britney-if-u-seek-amy-music-video-shoot |archivedate=2011-07-25}}</ref> It premiered on MTV's ''[[Total Request Live|TRL]]'' on September 16, 2004, and on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s ''[[106 & Park]]'' on January 18, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040917/world.htm|title=Britney Spears in undated publicity photograph from her upcoming music video My Prerogative, which premiered on MTV's TRL on Thursday.|date=2004-09-17|accessdate=2015-08-24|newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1490929/britney-fans-you-can-stop-speculating-now-official-hits-lp-track-list-revealed/|title=Britney Fans, You Can Stop Speculating Now \u2014 Official Hits LP Track List Revealed|date=2004-09-13|accessdate=2015-08-24|publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref> According to Spears's mother Lynne, the video was \"about capturing gorgeous close-ups and very subtle movement\" since Spears could not do any choreography due to her knee injury at the \"[[Outrageous (song)|Outrageous]]\" music video shoot. She also described the video as \"[having] an element of old Hollywood glamour and mystery\".<ref name=lynne>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490551/20040825/spears_britney.jhtml|title=Britney To Marry Kevin Federline In 'My Prerogative' Video|date=2004-08-25|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n\nThe music video begins with Spears driving a [[Porsche 928]] at high speed in the Hollywood Hills.<ref name=paramour /><ref name=synopsis>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490312/20040817/spears_britney.jhtml|title=Britney Makes Party-Crashing Her Prerogative In Next Video|date=2004-08-17|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|publisher=MTV}}</ref> She crashes through a fence and lands into a pool inside a manor where a party is taking place. She emerges from the water and crawls in top of the car to sing the first verse.<ref name=synopsis /> Spears's brother Bryan makes a cameo in these scenes.<ref name=lynne /> After she leaves the pool, she enters the manor and passes couples making out around her. She appears in a [[stainless steel]] kitchen, where a maid cuts the straps of her black wet dress. In the next scene, she walks into a study in which her husband at the time, Kevin Federline, is smoking and watching a black-and-white video of Spears on a [[projection screen]]. According to Jennifer Vineyard from [[MTV]], the clip had the style of [[pornographic film]]s from the 1940s and 1950s.<ref name=synopsis /> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in their article \"Britney Spears: The Complete Video Guide\", compared it to Madonna's performances of her 1984 single \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\".<ref name=rstone>{{cite magazine |url=|title=The Complete Video Guide: \"My Prerogative\"|year=2009|work=Rolling Stone|last=Reporter|first=Rolling Stone|ref=harv}}</ref> She then entered a dressing room with mirrors, wearing lingerie, high heels, stockings and a short fur jacket. She proceeds to a bedroom, in which a black dress is laid out on the comforter. She puts on the new dress and the camera cuts to the party outside where people gathered waiting.<ref name=synopsis /> During the song's bridge, it is revealed that the party is actually Spears's wedding, as she starts walking towards the aisle and Federline waits next to a priest. The video ends with a shot of the black-and-white video and Spears looking into the camera.<ref name=lynne /> The black-and-white footage was released as an alternate version of the music video in the 2004 DVD ''[[Greatest Hits: My Prerogative (video)|Greatest Hits: My Prerogative]]''.<ref name=dvd>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1493176/20041027/spears_britney.jhtml?headlines=true|title=Britney DVD Has Alternate Takes Of Her Videos, Plus More Skin|date=2004-10-27|accessdate=2010-03-19| last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n\n===Track listings